The following class contains the following code:

*{{com.atlassian.jira.vcs.DefaultRepositoryManager.public void updateRepository(Long, String, String, String, Properties)}}*
{code}
// Workout the difference between the sets
keys.removeAll(keys);

// Remove all the old keys that are not present any more
for (Iterator iterator = keys.iterator(); iterator.hasNext();)
{
    String key = (String) iterator.next();
    cvsPropertySet.remove(key);
}
{code}

Looking at the code one can observe that {{keys.removeAll(keys);}} effectively removes all elements of itself (same as {{clear()}} would do) and then tries to iterate over an empty collection. The line
{code}
keys.removeAll(keys);
{code}
is obviously meant to be
{code}
keys.removeAll(properties.keySet());
{code}

*NOTE: This needs verification!*
I have not had the time to test it. One can test it by setting some extra properties that are not in UI (alter code or set them in DB), then set the properties from UI and see if they are removed.

This part is somehow hard coded in the {{createissue-details.jsp}}. It should use the defined css class (as the alignment of this part will not take effect when changes made in {{global-static.css}}).
{code}
<tr>
        <td bgcolor=fffff0 align=right><webwork:text name="'issue.field.issuetype'"/>:</td>
        <td bgcolor=ffffff valign=top>
{code}

As a quick fix, we can replace the {{align=right}} with {{class=fieldLabelArea}}. For example:
{code}
<tr>
        <td bgcolor=fffff0 class=fieldLabelArea><webwork:text name="'issue.field.issuetype'"/>:</td>
        <td bgcolor=ffffff valign=top>
{code}

